ce:section.ce:para:
The high consumption rate and a limited reserve of fossil energy resources, and severe environmental impacts, have been the main drivers for developing renewable and sustainable energy resources. However, due to the intermittent nature of such renewable energy resources, efficient and cost-effective energy storage solutions are vital [1]. Battery is one of the well-devloped technologies for efficient storage of electrical energy, which has been in commercial use over many decades. For metal-air batteries such as Lithium-air (Li-air) and lithium-oxygen (Li-O2), a highly efficient oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) based electrocatalyst is a vital requirement. Among all the electrocatalysts for ORR, noble metals, especially Platinum (Pt), show the best and promising performance as the cathode material [2,3]. However, the high cost of precious Pt metal and scarcity nature limit the Pt-based catalysts from being widely employed in commercial applications [4,5]. Accordingly, significant research efforts should be devoted to developing high efficiency and cost-effective non-Pt-based new generation ORR catalysts. To date, various literature has reported designing highly-active noble metal-free catalysts for ORR. For example, carbon-based nanomaterials (such as activated carbon, graphene, carbon nanotubes, carbon nanofiber) [6–8], and non-precious metal oxides transition metal oxides (such as RuO2, MnO2, Ni(OH)2, and Fe2O3 [
                        9–12
                     ], conducting polymers (polyanilines and polythiophenes) [13,14], and their composites [15–17] have been actively studied as electrocatalysts.
